We were asked to consult for the patient's recently resected rectal cancer.

[end section id="20102"]

[start section id="20103"]

Mr. Klassen is a very pleasant 75-year-old male from APO New York, New York whose oncologic history is as follows:
1.  March 16, 2010, the patient underwent a colonoscopy for screening.  Three lesions were noted with two of them being polyps with low-grade dysplasia and the third one being approximately 3-cm in the distal rectum near the dentate that initially, on outside pathology, was indeterminate for adenocarcinoma but review here at Camelot Medical Center showed invasive grade 2 (of 4) adenocarcinoma.
2.  April 21, 2010, the patient was evaluated by the GI Team here at Camelot Medical Center.  A CT-scan of the chest, abdomen, and pelvis showed a few very minimally prominent perirectal lymph nodes.  A CEA checked at that time was 1.4.
3.  April 22, 2010, a rectal endoscopic ultrasound and FNA were completed.  On the EUS, the tumor appeared as a T2 tumor invading into the muscularis propria and also into the proximal portion of the sphincter.  The nodal appearance on EUS also appeared as an N1.  The FNA of the sample lymph node, however, was negative.
4.  April 30, 2010, Dr. Gilbert completed a laparoscopic APR which had to be converted to an open procedure due to anatomical reasons.  The pathology showed moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma measuring 2.2 x 1.7 x 1-cm and noted to be invading into the muscularis propria.  The margins were negative, and 4 of the 27 sampled lymph nodes were positive.  Four tumor deposits were noted in the perirectal adipose tissue.  The patient was thus staged as a T2, N2a, M0, stage IIIB rectal cancer.
We were asked to consult on Mr. Klassen's followup care due to his recently resected rectal cancer.  The patient is currently recovering from his surgery and overall doing well.  He has minimal to no complaints today.  He continues to have an NG tube in place.  He says his pain is overall controlled.  Otherwise, he denies any fevers, chills, sweats, chest pain, shortness-of-breath.

[end section id="20103"]

